-What did you say?

00:42:06.614 --> 00:42:08.280
-I said they're not
good enough for him.

00:42:08.280 --> 00:42:10.170
Every Jane is giving
him the thermometer,

00:42:10.170 --> 00:42:12.762
and he feels they're
just a waste of time.

00:42:12.762 --> 00:42:16.530
He's returning to his book,
he's deeply immersed in it.

00:42:16.530 --> 00:42:18.780
He sees no one except--
watch his head turn

00:42:18.780 --> 00:42:20.230
when that kid goes by.

00:42:20.230 --> 00:42:21.565
Won't do you any good, dear.

00:42:21.565 --> 00:42:23.580
He's a bookworm, but
swing them anyway.

00:42:23.580 --> 00:42:25.700
Oh, now how about this one?

00:42:25.700 --> 00:42:28.245
How would you like that
hanging on your Christmas tree?

00:42:28.245 --> 00:42:28.953
Oh, you wouldn't?

00:42:28.953 --> 00:42:32.057
Well, what is your
weakness brother?

00:42:32.057 --> 00:42:33.640
DAVID THORBURN: So
Stanwyck has become

00:42:33.640 --> 00:42:36.134
the narrator of this scene.

00:42:36.134 --> 00:42:38.300
But see what intelligence
she shows, what knowledge.

00:42:42.248 --> 00:42:45.092
-Look at that girl
over to his left.

00:42:45.092 --> 00:42:47.310
Look over to your
left, bookworm.

00:42:47.310 --> 00:42:49.040
There's a girl pining for you.

00:42:49.040 --> 00:42:50.880
A little further.

00:42:50.880 --> 00:42:52.730
Just a little further.

00:42:52.730 --> 00:42:53.590
There.

00:42:53.590 --> 00:42:54.870
Wasn't that worth looking for?

00:42:54.870 --> 00:42:56.828
See those nice store
teeth, all beaming at you.

00:42:56.828 --> 00:42:58.000
Well, she recognises you.

00:42:58.000 --> 00:43:00.146
She up, she's down, she
can't make up her mind.

00:43:00.146 --> 00:43:00.770
She's up again.

00:43:00.770 --> 00:43:02.811
DAVID THORBURN: I hope
you see how brilliant this

00:43:02.811 --> 00:43:04.210
is because look
in her hand here,

00:43:04.210 --> 00:43:05.365
we're looking at this
through the mirror

00:43:05.365 --> 00:43:06.650
as she's narrating it to us.

00:43:06.650 --> 00:43:08.775
-Went to manual training
school with in Louisville?

00:43:08.775 --> 00:43:09.650
Oh, you're not?

00:43:09.650 --> 00:43:11.400
Well, you certainly
look exactly like him,

00:43:11.400 --> 00:43:13.105
it's certainly a
remarkable resemblance.

00:43:13.105 --> 00:43:14.450
But if you're not going
to ask me to sit down,

00:43:14.450 --> 00:43:16.491
I suppose you're not going
to ask me to sit down.

00:43:16.491 --> 00:43:18.114
I'm very sorry, I
certainly hope I

00:43:18.114 --> 00:43:20.280
haven't caused you any
embarrassment, you so-and-so.

00:43:22.902 --> 00:43:24.830
I wonder if my
tie's on straight.

00:43:24.830 --> 00:43:26.890
I certainly upset them, don't I?

00:43:26.890 --> 00:43:28.850
Now who else is after me.

00:43:28.850 --> 00:43:30.820
Ah, the lady champion wrestler.

00:43:30.820 --> 00:43:32.530
Wouldn't she make a houseful?

00:43:32.530 --> 00:43:33.780
Oh, you don't like her either?

00:43:33.780 --> 00:43:35.360
Well, what are going
to do about it?

00:43:35.360 --> 00:43:36.860
Oh, you just can't
stand it anymore.

00:43:36.860 --> 00:43:38.610
You're leaving, these
women don't give you

00:43:38.610 --> 00:43:39.750
a moment's peace, do they?

00:43:39.750 --> 00:43:40.500
Well, go ahead.

00:43:40.500 --> 00:43:41.930
Go sulk in your cabin.

00:43:41.930 --> 00:43:43.430
Go soak your head
and see if I care.

00:43:47.374 --> 00:43:48.360
-Very sorry, sir.

00:43:59.476 --> 00:44:01.100
-Why don't you look
where you're going?

00:44:01.100 --> 00:44:01.890
-Why don't I look?

00:44:01.890 --> 00:44:03.566
-Look what you did to my shoe,
you knocked the heel off.

00:44:03.566 --> 00:44:04.065
-Oh, I did?

00:44:04.065 --> 00:44:05.230
Well, I'm certainly sorry.

00:44:05.230 --> 00:44:07.120
-You did, and you can just
take me right down to my cabin

00:44:07.120 --> 00:44:08.328
for another pair of slippers.

00:44:08.328 --> 00:44:09.400
-Oh, well certainly.

00:44:09.400 --> 00:44:10.070
It's the least I can do.

00:44:10.070 --> 00:44:11.200
By the way, my name's Pike.

00:44:11.200 --> 00:44:12.160
-Oh, everybody knows that.

00:44:12.160 --> 00:44:13.400
Nobody's talking
about anything else.

00:44:13.400 --> 00:44:14.620
This is my father
Colonel Harrington.

00:44:14.620 --> 00:44:16.161
My name is Gene,
it's really Eugenia.

00:44:16.161 --> 00:44:17.992
Come on.

00:44:17.992 --> 00:44:19.800
[END PLAYBACK]

00:44:19.800 --> 00:44:21.300
DAVID THORBURN: I
hope you recognize

00:44:21.300 --> 00:44:24.090
the tremendous
intelligence and wit that

00:44:24.090 --> 00:44:25.407
was embedded in that dialogue.

00:44:25.407 --> 00:44:26.490
That was a little too low.

00:44:26.490 --> 00:44:28.340
What is revealed
about that character,

00:44:28.340 --> 00:44:31.390
dramatized about that character,
in that opening scene,

00:44:31.390 --> 00:44:33.740
tells us almost everything
we need to know about her.

00:44:33.740 --> 00:44:36.320
Not everything, but
almost everything.

00:44:36.320 --> 00:44:38.820
And you can feel
the energy, the wit.

00:44:38.820 --> 00:44:41.320
And of course, who's in
control of that scene?

00:44:41.320 --> 00:44:43.410
Not the man, but the woman.

00:44:43.410 --> 00:44:47.570
Now let's look at another
scene from Howard Hawks

00:44:47.570 --> 00:44:49.110
film, Ball of Fire.

00:44:49.110 --> 00:44:52.120
The basic situation is Gary
Cooper, the man in the middle

00:44:52.120 --> 00:44:55.640
here, this fellow Gary
Cooper is the head

00:44:55.640 --> 00:44:58.640
of a consortium of
scholars who are compiling

00:44:58.640 --> 00:45:00.610
a dictionary of the
English language,

00:45:00.610 --> 00:45:05.620
with special emphasis on
colloquial or slang English.

00:45:05.620 --> 00:45:10.384
And earlier in the film, Gary
Cooper went to a nightclub.

00:45:10.384 --> 00:45:12.800
And he saw the Barbara Stanwyck
character, who is actually

00:45:12.800 --> 00:45:18.030
the mistress of a mob boss,
do a song and dance number.

00:45:18.030 --> 00:45:19.990
He spoke to her,
he interviewed her,

00:45:19.990 --> 00:45:22.240
and he became very excited
by what she represented.

00:45:22.240 --> 00:45:26.640
By the linguistic resources,
the verbal realities

00:45:26.640 --> 00:45:30.490
of the American language
that he'd been oblivious to.

00:45:30.490 --> 00:45:32.660
And he wants her to
contribute to his project.

00:45:32.660 --> 00:45:34.300
She's not interested.

00:45:34.300 --> 00:45:39.680
When she shows up at the lair
of the men of the scholars,

00:45:39.680 --> 00:45:44.120
when she invades the
nest of scholars,

00:45:44.120 --> 00:45:46.640
she does it because--
although you don't know that

00:45:46.640 --> 00:45:49.201
from seeing this clip,
but viewers of the film

00:45:49.201 --> 00:45:51.200
would know it-- because
she's really on the run.

00:45:51.200 --> 00:45:54.160
She's afraid that her
boyfriend, the mob boss,

00:45:54.160 --> 00:45:55.680
is going to bump her off.

00:45:55.680 --> 00:45:57.030
So she needs to hide out.

00:45:57.030 --> 00:45:58.910
And that's really
why she's come here.

00:45:58.910 --> 00:45:59.430
All right.

00:45:59.430 --> 00:46:02.290
So here is this scene
from Ball of Fire.

00:46:02.290 --> 00:46:03.490
[VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:46:03.490 --> 00:46:04.620
